english:
  title: Preface to the Literary Collection of Lee Ja-an of Kyungsan
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The sun, moon, and stars are Heaven's patterns. Mountains, rivers, and vegetation are Earth's patterns. Poetry, histories, rites, and music are Man's patterns. Yet Heaven operates through vital force, Earth through form, while Man operates through Way. Thus it is said: "Pattern is the vessel that bears the Way"—speaking of human culture. When humans grasp this Way, the teachings of poetry, histories, rites, and music illuminate all under Heaven. The three luminaries proceed in harmony, and the ten thousand things are ordered aright. The flourishing of culture reaches its apex here.

    When a scholar is born between Heaven and Earth, he absorbs their subtle essence and expresses it through writing. Some present their work at the imperial court; others serve in the domains of princes. So did Yin Jifu compose the "Mu Ru" odes in Zhou, and Shi Ke present the "Wu Xie" hymns in Lu. When we reach the Spring and Autumn period, the great officers of the various states, traveling to diplomatic functions, composed verse with skill, moving men through imagery and expressing their aspirations. Such were Shu Xiang of Jin and Zichan of Zheng. In the Han's golden age, Dong Zhongshu and Jia Yi presented policy papers and epistles, illuminating the mysteries of Heaven and Man, discussing the essentials of good governance. Meanwhile, Mei Sheng and Sima Xiangru wandered among princely courts, their brilliant prose adorning the virtue of culture.

    Our Eastern realm, though beyond the seas, has revered Chinese refinement throughout the ages. Scholars of letters have appeared without ceasing. In Koguryo there was Ulchi Mundeok; in Silla, Choe Chiwon. In our founding dynasty, Minister Kim Bu-sik and Academician Lee Kyu-bo were preeminent. In recent times, great Confucians like Master Lee of Gyerim, called the Beneficial Recluse, first championed the study of ancient prose. Master Lee of Hansan, called the Farming Recluse, and Master Lee of Kyungsan, called the Woodcutter Recluse, followed in harmony. Now Master Lee of Mogen, having received the teachings of his family and studied in the Central Plain, obtained proper guidance from worthy teachers and friends, investigated the mysteries of human nature and moral virtue, returned to our realm, and gathered scholars to instruct. Those moved to awaken were: Master Jeong Dal-ga of Ocheon, Master Lee Ja-an of Kyungsan, Master Park Sang-chung of Panyang, Master Park Ja-heo of Milyang, Master Kim Gyeong-ji of Yeonghae, Master Kwon Ga-won, and Master Yun So-jong of Mosong. Though I myself am unworthy, I too was counted among these worthies.

    Among them, Ja-an possesses a penetrating and luminous mind, surpassing all others. When he hears the Master's teachings, he grasps them silently, understanding in his heart without needing to ask twice. In what he alone perceives, he transcends ordinary comprehension. He reads broadly through all texts and retains whatever he sees at a glance. His collected writings in poetry and prose are grounded in the stimulating and comparative methods of the *Book of Poetry* and the canonical models of the *Book of History*. Their harmony and refinement, their brilliance and flourishing—all arise from rites and music. Can one not deeply versed in the Way accomplish such things?

    The Ming Dynasty, having received the Mandate of Heaven, with the Emperor ruling all under Heaven, cultivates virtue and refrains from war, unifying all civilization. In establishing rites and composing music, in transforming and perfecting human culture, in ordering Heaven and Earth—this is the age. The documents our kingdom sends in service to the great are largely composed by Ja-an. The Emperor, viewing them, praised them saying, "The rhetoric of these memorials rings true and sincere." Now, fulfilling seasonal duties, he crosses into Liaodong and Shenyang, traverses the domains of Qi and Lu, crosses the turbulent Yellow River, and enters the imperial court. What insight and inspiration might he gain from such observation?

    Alas, when Ji Zha journeyed to Lu to observe the music of Zhou, he was able to recognize its virtue and magnificence. Ja-an's journey comes at the very height of the Ming's cultural creation. Surely he will crystallize what he observes and feels, recording merit and praising virtue, becoming the elegant odes of the Ming, worthy to stand beside the achievements of Yin Jifu. When Ja-an returns and shows his work to me, I shall entitle it the *Collection of Observations on Splendor*.
